[319-py]
LEVEL=py
JQ = {{{
map(.[1] as $needle | .[0] | contains($needle))
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[[[],[]], [[1,2,3], [1,2]], [[1,2,3], [3,1]], [[1,2,3], [4]], [[1,2,3], [1,4]]]
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
[true, true, true, false, false]
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$py=[all(x in pair[0] for x in pair[1]) for pair in _]"}
}}}
COMMENT=Array contains() here reduces to "every needle element is a member of the haystack array" since elements are plain scalars — doesn't cover jq's fuller recursive containment for nested containers.

[320-py]
LEVEL=py
JQ = {{{
map(.[1] as $needle | .[0] | contains($needle))
}}}
INPUT = {{{
[[["foobar", "foobaz"], ["baz", "bar"]], [["foobar", "foobaz"], ["foo"]], [["foobar", "foobaz"], ["blap"]]]
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
[true, true, false]
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": "$py=[all(any(x in h for h in pair[0]) for x in pair[1]) for pair in _]"}
}}}
COMMENT=Here containment is substring-based (needle strings need only be a substring of some haystack string, not an exact match) — Python's "in" does substring checks naturally for str-in-str.

[321-nav]
LEVEL=nav
JQ = {{{
[({foo: 12, bar:13} | contains({foo: 12})), ({foo: 12} | contains({})), ({foo: 12, bar:13} | contains({baz:14}))]
}}}
INPUT = {{{
{}
}}}
EXPECTED = {{{
[true, true, false]
}}}
JFTL = {{{
{"main": [true, true, false]}
}}}
COMMENT=All operands are literals embedded in the jq program itself, and input ({}) is never referenced — fully deterministic, hence a pure literal.

[322-nav]
